alternatives.transcript: leslie palmer is a sixty two year old female presenting to the emergency department with fatigue heart palpitations and dyspnea both exertionally and arrest patients stated that she'd been experiencing symptoms for around two months with gradual worsening and was instructed to go to the ed as per her primary care provider patient denies any chest pain or any other pain patient is a well developed well nourished sixty two year old female in no immediate distress upon entering exam room patient states she has a history of hypertension and sarcoidosis reports cat cardiac catheterization one year ago with no major complications patient reports that her father died due to myocardial infarction at fifty nine years old and that her mother died at age forty from unknown causes patient's medications include lisinopril at ten milligrams once daily and prednisone ten milligrams once daily there are no known drug allergies patient needs a balanced diet no alcohol drug or tobacco use with moderate caffeine consumption patient states that she used to walk regularly but cannot anymore due to her symptoms patient is a elementary school teacher and is in a monogamous sexually active relationship her vitals are as follows heart rate of one ten beats per minute blood pressure of one thirty six over ninety nine respiratory rate of twenty she is satting ninety one on room air and her temperature is ninety eight point six degrees fahrenheit review system shows fatigue unexplained weight gain leg edema palpitations presyncope and dyspnea as well as orthopnea physical findings show jugular vein extension but no carotid bruise patient does have a systolic murmur with an s four no regurgitation with pmi displaced laterally bibasilar rails can be heard on lung auscultation peripheral leg edema is noted patient is negative for holman sign chest x-ray shows hilar lymphadenopathy but no pulmonary edema or cardiomegaly two d echo shows restrictive cardiomyopathy with a left ventricular ejection fraction of fifty five percent ekg shows sinus rhythm normal axis with a brief period of nonsustained ventricular tachycardia lab findings include negative troponin and a bnp of four thousand the differential diagnosis for this patient includes restrictive cardiomyopathy and heart failure but the most likely diagnosis is restrictive cardiomyopathy second to sarcoidosis given patient's history of sarcoidosis sarcoidosis and imaging findings showing hyaloid phagocytopathiopathy and restricted cardiomyopathy on the echo patient was admitted to telemetry with activity out of bed with assistance and nursing instructions to be given as follows strict monitoring of intakes and outputs daily weight checks dvt prophylaxis and o two therapy via nasal cannula with goal of maintaining oxygen saturation at ninety six percent patient is also placed on a low sodium diet and saline lock is initiated patient is to be continued on lisinopril ten milligrams once daily but the prednisone will be increased to sixty milligrams once daily and amiodarone one hundred fifty milligrams iv as well as furosemide forty milligrams iv should be started complete metabolic panel is ordered and a consult will be made to interventional cardiology for consult for implantation of an automatic implantable cardiover defibrillator or an ascd as well as a consult to nuclear medicine for an fdg
